<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,609,659]" box="[382,1270,609,630]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">
Measurements in mm: body length 1.15 (
<typeStatus box="[779,868,609,630]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">holotype</typeStatus>
), 1.07–1.21 (
<typeStatus box="[993,1090,609,630]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">paratypes</typeStatus>
), wing length 1.06
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,609,659]" box="[317,1170,638,659]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">
(
<typeStatus box="[324,413,638,659]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">holotype</typeStatus>
), 1.15 –1.37 (
<typeStatus box="[548,645,638,659]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">paratypes</typeStatus>
), wing width 0.41 (
<typeStatus box="[837,926,638,659]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">holotype</typeStatus>
), 0.46 –0.54 (
<typeStatus box="[1061,1159,638,659]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">paratypes</typeStatus>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,696,1379]" box="[382,988,696,717]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Body dark greyish brown, mesonotum with some weak shine.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,696,1379]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">
Mouth edge less protruding than in the other Afrotropical species, inter-antennal triangle continued in a sagittal ridge. Although this ridge is slightly concave, it supports 2 more concave hollows below antennae. 3 medium long pairs of interfrontal setae (longest one 
<quantity box="[997,1086,782,803]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="mm" value="0.05">0.05 mm</quantity>
), and a 4th anterior minute interfrontal (not seen on 
<typeStatus box="[627,715,811,832]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">holotype</typeStatus>
). Gena below eye 
<quantity box="[892,981,811,832]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="mm" value="0.06">0.06 mm</quantity>
, longest (oblique) diameter of eye 
<quantity box="[357,445,840,861]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="mm" value="0.19">0.19 mm</quantity>
. Genal seta 
<quantity box="[562,650,840,861]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="mm" value="0.07">0.07 mm</quantity>
. Arista 
<quantity box="[725,810,840,861]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="mm" value="0.41">0.41 mm</quantity>
long (not precisely measurable along its curvature). Aristal cilia at most 
<quantity box="[577,678,868,889]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="mm" value="0.015">0.015 mm</quantity>
, cilia on first flagellomere apically even shorter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,696,1379]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">
Wing (
<figureCitation box="[448,518,897,918]" captionStart="Figs 56–57" captionStartId="19.[317,360,1775,1796]" captionTargetBox="[356,1230,888,1747]" captionTargetId="figure-138@19.[356,1230,888,1747]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figs 56–57. Opacifrons spp., left wing of paratypes. 56 = O. afrobrevisecunda sp. n.; 57 = O. subserrata sp. n." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5735759" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5735759/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Fig. 56</figureCitation>
) without any pattern. Veins yellowish. Costal ratio 
<quantity box="[1011,1096,897,918]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="mm" value="0.22">0.22 mm</quantity>
/ 
<quantity box="[1114,1202,897,918]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="mm" value="0.37">0.37 mm</quantity>
, i.e. 60 (
<typeStatus box="[324,414,926,947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">holotype</typeStatus>
). Vein R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[500,520,938,950]" fontSize="5" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">2+3</subScript>
more arcuately curved than in the other Afrotropical species. Inter-crossvein section 
<quantity box="[389,476,955,976]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.10 mm</quantity>
, M-M crossvein 
<quantity box="[633,716,955,976]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="mm" value="0.06">0.06 mm</quantity>
(
<typeStatus box="[728,817,955,976]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">holotype</typeStatus>
), ratio about 2.0 in the 
<typeStatus box="[1028,1185,955,976]" isOtherTypeStatus="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">other specimens</typeStatus>
. Knob of halter dirty yellow, stalk greyish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,696,1379]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">
Legs all yellowish brown on 
<typeStatus box="[653,737,1012,1033]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">holotype</typeStatus>
(discoloured), actually darker brown, coxae, trochanters and small parts of pleura reddish. Anterodorsal setae on mid tibia at 9/27 and at 17/27 (small) a dorsal seta at 21/27 and a comparatively small posterodorsal at 22/27. Ventral seta on mid basitarsus comparatively short.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,696,1379]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">
Abdominal tergal setae comparatively short. Male sternite 5 with a paired, almost symmetrical pair of caudal processes (
<figureCitation box="[556,642,1156,1177]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="5.[317,360,1551,1572]" captionTargetBox="[320,1267,446,1515]" captionTargetId="figure-10@5.[317,1270,443,1516]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 1–8. 1–7 = Opacifrons afrobrevisecunda sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 1 = sternite 5, ventral view, 2 = same, medio-caudal part in higher magnification, 3 = postabdominal sclerites (synsternite), ventral view, 4 = subepandrial sclerite (inside) and modified cerci, caudal view (outset: cercal peg at its longest), 5 = postgonite, broadest (slightly sublateral) view, 6 = surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view, 7 = phallus, lateral view. 8 = O. brevisecunda L. PAPP, a male from Taiwan, surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5735741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5735741/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Figs 1–2</figureCitation>
, cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="PAPP, L." box="[681,785,1156,1177]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" pagination="225 - 251" refId="ref10297" refString="PAPP, L. (1991) Oriental Limosininae: new species and records (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae). Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae 37 (3 - 4): 225 - 251." type="journal article" year="1991">PAPP 1991</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 42). Sternite 6 part of the syntergosternite thin medially and on the right side and definitely lengthened to the right. Subepandrial sclerite of a specific shape, cercal part of the epandrial complex high, cercal pegs just below its mid level, cercal peg comparatively small. Surstylus subquadrate (
<figureCitation box="[749,808,1243,1264]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="5.[317,360,1551,1572]" captionTargetBox="[320,1267,446,1515]" captionTargetId="figure-10@5.[317,1270,443,1516]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 1–8. 1–7 = Opacifrons afrobrevisecunda sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 1 = sternite 5, ventral view, 2 = same, medio-caudal part in higher magnification, 3 = postabdominal sclerites (synsternite), ventral view, 4 = subepandrial sclerite (inside) and modified cerci, caudal view (outset: cercal peg at its longest), 5 = postgonite, broadest (slightly sublateral) view, 6 = surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view, 7 = phallus, lateral view. 8 = O. brevisecunda L. PAPP, a male from Taiwan, surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5735741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5735741/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
, cf. 
<figureCitation box="[848,904,1243,1264]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="5.[317,360,1551,1572]" captionTargetBox="[320,1267,446,1515]" captionTargetId="figure-10@5.[317,1270,443,1516]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 1–8. 1–7 = Opacifrons afrobrevisecunda sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 1 = sternite 5, ventral view, 2 = same, medio-caudal part in higher magnification, 3 = postabdominal sclerites (synsternite), ventral view, 4 = subepandrial sclerite (inside) and modified cerci, caudal view (outset: cercal peg at its longest), 5 = postgonite, broadest (slightly sublateral) view, 6 = surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view, 7 = phallus, lateral view. 8 = O. brevisecunda L. PAPP, a male from Taiwan, surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5735741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5735741/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="PAPP, L." box="[951,1055,1243,1264]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" pagination="225 - 251" refId="ref10297" refString="PAPP, L. (1991) Oriental Limosininae: new species and records (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae). Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae 37 (3 - 4): 225 - 251." type="journal article" year="1991">PAPP 1991</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 43) with a caudal subapical thorn, caudal (posterior) margin with a few setae only. Distiphallus (
<figureCitation box="[1073,1131,1272,1293]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="5.[317,360,1551,1572]" captionTargetBox="[320,1267,446,1515]" captionTargetId="figure-10@5.[317,1270,443,1516]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 1–8. 1–7 = Opacifrons afrobrevisecunda sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 1 = sternite 5, ventral view, 2 = same, medio-caudal part in higher magnification, 3 = postabdominal sclerites (synsternite), ventral view, 4 = subepandrial sclerite (inside) and modified cerci, caudal view (outset: cercal peg at its longest), 5 = postgonite, broadest (slightly sublateral) view, 6 = surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view, 7 = phallus, lateral view. 8 = O. brevisecunda L. PAPP, a male from Taiwan, surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5735741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5735741/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) with a strong apical, dorsally curved process, postgonite (
<figureCitation box="[746,804,1300,1321]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="5.[317,360,1551,1572]" captionTargetBox="[320,1267,446,1515]" captionTargetId="figure-10@5.[317,1270,443,1516]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 1–8. 1–7 = Opacifrons afrobrevisecunda sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 1 = sternite 5, ventral view, 2 = same, medio-caudal part in higher magnification, 3 = postabdominal sclerites (synsternite), ventral view, 4 = subepandrial sclerite (inside) and modified cerci, caudal view (outset: cercal peg at its longest), 5 = postgonite, broadest (slightly sublateral) view, 6 = surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view, 7 = phallus, lateral view. 8 = O. brevisecunda L. PAPP, a male from Taiwan, surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5735741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5735741/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) long, comparatively thin and curved.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,696,1379]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">
Female unknown but probably close to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. PAPP" authorityYear="1991" box="[773,932,1329,1350]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Opacifrons" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevisecunda">
<emphasis box="[773,932,1329,1350]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">O. brevisecunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, incl. cerci and spermathecae (see 
<bibRefCitation author="PAPP, L." box="[317,423,1358,1379]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" pagination="225 - 251" refId="ref10297" refString="PAPP, L. (1991) Oriental Limosininae: new species and records (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae). Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae 37 (3 - 4): 225 - 251." type="journal article" year="1991">PAPP 1991</bibRefCitation>
: figs 40–41).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,1419,1762]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">
The relationships of this new species cannot be judged by the key below. Indeed, it is very different from the rest of the Afrotropical species. Actually 
<taxonomicName authority="Papp, 2012" authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Opacifrons" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afrobrevisecunda" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">O. afrobrevisecunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[530,592,1489,1515]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="L. PAPP, 1991" authorityName="L. PAPP" authorityYear="1991" box="[834,1203,1489,1515]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Opacifrons" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevisecunda">
<emphasis box="[834,1026,1489,1515]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">O. brevisecunda</emphasis>
L. 
<bibRefCitation author="PAPP, L." box="[1067,1203,1489,1515]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" pagination="225 - 251" refId="ref10297" refString="PAPP, L. (1991) Oriental Limosininae: new species and records (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae). Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae 37 (3 - 4): 225 - 251." type="journal article" year="1991">PAPP, 1991</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but I found some details in the male genitalia, which are distinctive enough to define another species. The caudal processes of sternite 
<quantity box="[861,905,1559,1585]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" unit="in" value="5.0">5 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2012" box="[912,1152,1560,1586]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Opacifrons" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afrobrevisecunda">
<emphasis box="[912,1152,1560,1586]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">O. afrobrevisecunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males are distinctly longer (
<figureCitation box="[544,660,1595,1621]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="5.[317,360,1551,1572]" captionTargetBox="[320,1267,446,1515]" captionTargetId="figure-10@5.[317,1270,443,1516]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 1–8. 1–7 = Opacifrons afrobrevisecunda sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 1 = sternite 5, ventral view, 2 = same, medio-caudal part in higher magnification, 3 = postabdominal sclerites (synsternite), ventral view, 4 = subepandrial sclerite (inside) and modified cerci, caudal view (outset: cercal peg at its longest), 5 = postgonite, broadest (slightly sublateral) view, 6 = surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view, 7 = phallus, lateral view. 8 = O. brevisecunda L. PAPP, a male from Taiwan, surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5735741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5735741/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Figs 1–2</figureCitation>
, cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="PAPP, L." box="[731,871,1595,1621]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" pagination="225 - 251" refId="ref10297" refString="PAPP, L. (1991) Oriental Limosininae: new species and records (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae). Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae 37 (3 - 4): 225 - 251." type="journal article" year="1991">PAPP 1991</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 42). The surstylus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. PAPP" authorityYear="1991" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Opacifrons" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevisecunda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">O. brevisecunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[492,563,1630,1656]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="5.[317,360,1551,1572]" captionTargetBox="[320,1267,446,1515]" captionTargetId="figure-10@5.[317,1270,443,1516]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 1–8. 1–7 = Opacifrons afrobrevisecunda sp. n., paratype male, postabdomen and genitalia. 1 = sternite 5, ventral view, 2 = same, medio-caudal part in higher magnification, 3 = postabdominal sclerites (synsternite), ventral view, 4 = subepandrial sclerite (inside) and modified cerci, caudal view (outset: cercal peg at its longest), 5 = postgonite, broadest (slightly sublateral) view, 6 = surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view, 7 = phallus, lateral view. 8 = O. brevisecunda L. PAPP, a male from Taiwan, surstylus, broadest (sublateral-subventral) view. Scales: 0.2 mm for Figs" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5735741" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5735741/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) has more and much longer setae posteriorly than the new species (it is true also for the 
<typeStatus box="[687,749,1665,1691]" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">types</typeStatus>
but those setae were omitted from PAPP’ s (1991) fig. 43). It is conspicuous that the distiphallus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. PAPP" authorityYear="1991" box="[981,1174,1700,1726]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Opacifrons" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevisecunda">
<emphasis box="[981,1174,1700,1726]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">O. brevisecunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more curved, and consequently the distiphallus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Papp" authorityYear="2012" box="[858,1102,1736,1762]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Opacifrons" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afrobrevisecunda">
<emphasis box="[858,1102,1736,1762]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="125">O. afrobrevisecunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems longer
</paragraph>
